  'HEDGE-PIG': Etymology(meta: 'ARCHAIC · archaic', note: 'An Elizabethan word for hedgehog. The Macbeth witches chant \'Thrice the brinded cat hath mew\'d, thrice and once the hedge-pig whin\'d\' — associating the creature with dark magic.'),
  'HELLFIRE': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'Southern US; intensifier of \'hell\'.'),
  'HOG-TIED': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'Cowboy origin — to tie a hog\'s legs; \'stuck, restrained\'.'),
  'HOGWASH': Etymology(meta: '', note: 'Originally slop fed to pigs; figurative by 18th C.'),
  'HOLY COW': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: '1920s US sportscaster catchphrase (Harry Caray, Phil Rizzuto).'),
  'HOLY MACKEREL': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'Early 20th C US; possibly anti-Catholic origin (Friday fish).'),
  'HOLY MOLY': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: '1920s US; later popularised by Captain Marvel comics.'),
  'HOLY SMOKES': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'Early 20th C US; euphemism for \'holy smoke of incense\'.'),
  'HOLY TOLEDO': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'Toledo, Spain was a centre of medieval Christendom — \'Holy Toledo!\' substitutes for \'Holy God!\' Sports broadcaster Milo Hamilton popularised it calling baseball games in the 1960s.'),
  'HOOEY': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: '1920s US slang; possibly from Russian/Yiddish.'),
  'HORNSWOGGLE': Etymology(meta: 'US · Victorian', note: 'Early 19th C US frontier slang; \'to cheat or swindle\'.'),
  'HORSEFEATHERS': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: '1920s US; coined by cartoonist Billy DeBeck as a minced euphemism.'),
  'HUMBUG': Etymology(meta: '', note: 'Mid-18th C; made famous by Dickens\' Scrooge.'),
  'I\'LL BE': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'Truncated \'I\'ll be damned\'; Southern US.'),
  'JACKANAPES': Etymology(meta: 'ARCHAIC · archaic', note: 'Originally \'Jack Napes\', a nickname for William de la Pole, Duke of Suffolk (d. 1450), whose badge was a ball and chain like a tethered ape. Came to mean any cheeky upstart.'),
  'JACKASS': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'From \'jack\' (male) + \'ass\' (donkey); insult use 17th C.'),
  'JANKY': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: '2000s US slang; \'shoddy, unreliable\'.'),
  'JEEPERS': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'Euphemism for \'Jesus Christ\'; 1920s US.'),
  'JEEZ': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'Minced form of \'Jesus\'; popularised 1920s US.'),
  'JIMINY': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'Euphemism for \'Jesus\'; popularised by Disney\'s Pinocchio (1940).'),
  'JOBSWORTH': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'From \'it\'s more than my job\'s worth\' — the cry of a petty bureaucrat who refuses to help. Coined by BBC\'s \'That\'s Life!\' show in the 1970s, which awarded a weekly \'Jobsworth of the Week\'.'),
  'KEELHAUL': Etymology(meta: 'historical', note: 'From Dutch \'kielhalen\' — to drag a person under the keel of a ship as punishment. The barnacle-encrusted hull would flay skin off. Now used figuratively: \'the boss will keelhaul me for this\'.'),
  'KHYBER': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'Cockney rhyming slang: \'Khyber Pass\' = arse. The Khyber Pass is a real mountain pass between Afghanistan and Pakistan — the British Army knew it well, which is probably how the rhyme originated.'),
  'KLUTZ': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'From Yiddish \'klots\' — block of wood; clumsy person.'),
  'KNACKERS': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'From \'knacker\' — a horse slaughterer; slang for testicles since 19th C.'),
  'KNAVE': Etymology(meta: 'ARCHAIC · Shakespearean', note: 'Old English \'cnafa\' — boy; meaning \'rogue\' by 13th C.'),
  'KNOB': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'From Middle English \'knobbe\' (a lump). As slang for penis since the 18th century (from the shape). \'Knobhead\' — literally \'penis-head\' — is a standard British insult that sounds funnier than it is rude.'),
  'KNUCKLEHEAD': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: '1940s US; popularised by Moe Howard of the Three Stooges.'),
  'KOOK': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: '1950s US surfer/beatnik slang; \'crazy person\'.'),
  'LANDLUBBER': Etymology(meta: 'historical', note: 'From \'land\' + \'lubber\' (a clumsy person, from Old English). Sailors used it from the 1570s to mock anyone useless at sea. A \'lubber\'s hole\' was an easy route up the mast that proper sailors avoided.'),
  'LARRIKIN': Etymology(meta: 'AU', note: 'First recorded in Melbourne in 1868, possibly from an Irish policeman\'s pronunciation of \'larking\'. Originally described young street toughs; now often used approvingly for a cheeky rebel.'),
  'LAYABOUT': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'One who \'lays about\' — i.e. lies around doing nothing. British slang since the 1930s. Often used in tabloid headlines about benefit claimants, dripping with moral disapproval.'),
  'LEMON': Etymology(meta: '', note: 'As slang for a defective product since the 1900s — originally an unsatisfactory car (\'lemon laws\' followed). As an insult for a person, it implies someone sour, foolish, or generally disappointing.'),
  'LEWDSTER': Etymology(meta: 'ARCHAIC · archaic', note: 'Shakespeare coined this in \'Merry Wives of Windsor\' by adding \'-ster\' to \'lewd\'. Originally \'lewd\' meant merely ignorant (from Old English \'laewede\', a layperson).'),
  'LOUT': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'From Old English \'lutan\' (to bow, stoop). By the 16th century it meant an awkward, clumsy person. Shakespeare used it as a verb in \'The Winter\'s Tale\' meaning to treat with contempt.'),
  'LUNKHEAD': Etymology(meta: 'US · Victorian', note: 'Mid-19th C US; \'lump\' + \'head\'.'),
  'LUVVIE': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'From actors\' habit of calling everyone \'love\' or \'luvvie darling\'. Private Eye magazine popularised it in the 1980s as a gently mocking term for pretentious thespians. Now standard British English.'),
  'MAGPIE': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'Magpies are known for stealing shiny objects and chattering incessantly. As an insult since the 17th century, it means either a thief or a person who won\'t stop talking.'),
  'MALARKEY': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: '1920s US; origin disputed — possibly from Irish surname.'),
  'MEANIE': Etymology(meta: '', note: 'From \'mean\' + \'-ie\' diminutive suffix. Children\'s standard insult since the 1920s. The Yellow Submarine (1968) featured the \'Blue Meanies\', cementing the word in pop culture.'),
  'MEATHEAD': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: '1940s US; popularised by \'All in the Family\' (1970s).'),
  'MERCY ME': Etymology(meta: 'US · Victorian', note: 'Southern US exclamation; truncated religious plea.'),
  'MINGER': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'From Scots dialect \'ming\' (to smell bad), possibly from Old English \'mengan\' (to mix). \'Minger\' exploded in 1990s British slang meaning an unattractive person. \'Minging\' means disgusting.'),
  'MISCREANT': Etymology(meta: 'ARCHAIC · archaic', note: 'From Old French \'mescreant\' (unbeliever) — originally a Crusades-era term for a non-Christian. By the 14th century it broadened to mean any villain or wretch, regardless of faith.'),
  'MOONCALF': Etymology(meta: 'UK · archaic', note: 'Originally a deformed calf thought to be caused by the moon\'s influence (16th century superstition). Shakespeare used it in \'The Tempest\' for Caliban. By Victorian times it meant a dreamy fool.'),
  'MOUNTEBANK': Etymology(meta: 'ARCHAIC · Victorian', note: 'From Italian \'monta in banco\' — one who climbs on a bench (to sell fake cures).'),
  'MUGGER': Etymology(meta: '', note: 'In theatre, \'mugging\' means making exaggerated facial expressions to get laughs — from \'mug\' (face, since the 1700s, probably from drinking mugs shaped like faces). A separate meaning from \'robber\'.'),
  'MUPPET': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: '1980s UK slang from Jim Henson\'s Muppets; gentle insult.'),
  'NAFF': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'Origin disputed — possibly Polari (gay slang) acronym \'Not Available For F***ing\', or from \'naff\' meaning a nothing/nobody. Princess Anne famously told paparazzi to \'naff off\' in 1982.'),
  'NARK': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'From Romani \'nak\' (nose). A \'nark\' was originally a police informer (one who \'noses around\'). \'Narky\' means irritable or bad-tempered. Both have been British slang since the 1840s.'),
  'NIMROD': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'Biblical hunter; inverted to \'fool\' by Bugs Bunny\'s mocking use (1940s).'),
  'NINNY': Etymology(meta: '', note: 'Possibly shortened from \'innocent\' or from the Spanish \'nino\' (child). Used since the 1590s — Shakespeare has \'ninnies\' in \'The Tempest\'. \'Ninnyhammer\' is the deluxe version.'),
  'NITWIT': Etymology(meta: '', note: '1920s, from \'nit\' (nothing) + wit.'),
  'NONG': Etymology(meta: 'AU', note: 'Australian slang from the 1940s, probably shortened from \'ning-nong\' (a fool). Used affectionately — \'don\'t be a nong\' — with no real venom behind it.'),
  'NOODLE': Etymology(meta: '', note: '\'Noodle\' has meant a fool since the 1750s, predating its food meaning in English. Possibly from \'noddle\' (head). \'Use your noodle\' — meaning use your head — preserves both senses simultaneously.'),
  'NUMPTY': Etymology(meta: 'SCO', note: 'Scots, late 20th C; origin uncertain — possibly from \'numps\' (fool).'),
  'NUTCASE': Etymology(meta: '', note: 'From \'nut\' (head, since the 1840s) + \'case\' (a hopeless instance). Emerged in the 1950s as a more emphatic version of \'nutty\'. \'Nutcase\' is now mild enough for children\'s TV.'),
  'NUTTY': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'From \'nut\' meaning head (since the 1840s). \'Nutty\' (crazy) and \'nutter\' (a crazy person) are standard British slang. Cockney \'off your nut\' means insane.'),
  'NYAFF': Etymology(meta: 'SCO', note: 'Scots for an annoying small person — like a yapping dog. From the sound of a small dog\'s bark. Used in Scottish Parliament in 2004, causing pearl-clutching among non-Scots.'),
  'OAFS': Etymology(meta: '', note: 'From Old Norse \'alfr\' (elf). An \'oaf\' was originally a changeling — a deformed child left by elves in place of a human baby. By the 1600s it just meant a stupid, clumsy person. The fairy-tale origin is completely forgotten.'),
  'OPE': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'Midwestern \'oh, excuse me\' — viral meme-famous from ~2015.'),
  'PALOOKA': Etymology(meta: 'US · Victorian', note: '1920s US boxing slang — a mediocre fighter; origin disputed.'),
  'PEANUT': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: '\'Peanut gallery\' = cheap seats for hecklers; vaudeville-era.'),
  'PHOOEY': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'From Yiddish \'feh\'; popularised 1920s.'),
  'PICKLE': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: '\'In a pickle\' dates to Shakespeare\'s \'The Tempest\' (1611). Calling a child \'a right little pickle\' means they are mischievous. The original pickle was the brine, not the cucumber.'),
  'PIFFLE': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'Probably imitative — suggesting something trivial blown away like air. Used since the 1840s to mean nonsense. Boris Johnson popularised \'piffle-paffle\' as a dismissal, adding a reduplicative flourish.'),
  'PIG': Etymology(meta: '', note: 'Derogatory use since 14th C.'),
  'PILLOCK': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'Originally northern English for penis; meaning \'fool\' from mid-20th C.'),
  'PLATES': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'Cockney rhyming slang: \'plates of meat\' = feet. One of the oldest and most recognisable examples of Cockney rhyming slang, attested from the 1850s.'),
  'PLEB': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'From Latin \'plebs\' (the common people of Rome, as opposed to patricians). In 2012, a UK cabinet minister called a police officer a \'pleb\' — the resulting \'Plebgate\' scandal cost him his job.'),
  'PLONK': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'Australian soldiers in WWI mangled French \'vin blanc\' (white wine) into \'plonk\'. It came to mean cheap, bad wine — and by extension, anything cheap and nasty. \'Don\'t drink that plonk!\''),
  'PLONKER': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'Originally slang for penis (1940s); meaning \'fool\' from 1980s sitcoms.'),
  'POGUE': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'Modern US military slang for a non-combat soldier.'),
  'POLTROON': Etymology(meta: 'ARCHAIC · archaic', note: 'From Italian \'poltrone\' (lazy person, coward), entering English via French in the 16th century. Shakespeare used it in \'All\'s Well That Ends Well\'.'),
  'PONCE': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'Originally slang for a pimp (from 1870s, possibly from French \'pensionnaire\'). In modern British English, \'ponce\' usually means an effeminate or pretentious man — \'don\'t be such a ponce\'.'),
  'POOPYHEAD': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'The nuclear option in playground insults since the 1970s. \'Poopyhead\' is the first compound insult most English-speaking children construct — a milestone in linguistic development, technically.'),
  'POPPYCOCK': Etymology(meta: '', note: 'From Dutch \'pappekak\' — soft dung. Polite now, very rude in origin.'),
  'PORKY': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'Cockney rhyming slang: \'porky pies\' = lies. \'Telling porkies\' is now standard British English, understood far beyond London\'s East End.'),
  'PRATS': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'Plural of \'prat\' — originally 16th century slang for buttocks (a \'pratfall\' is falling on your rear). Shifted to mean a fool by the 1960s. Now one of the most satisfying British insults.'),
  'PRIBBLING': Etymology(meta: 'ARCHAIC · archaic', note: 'Shakespearean adjective meaning petty or quarrelsome, used in compound insults like \'pribbling rogue\'. Appears in \'Troilus and Cressida\' (c. 1602).'),
  'PUTTOCK': Etymology(meta: 'ARCHAIC · archaic', note: 'A puttock is a red kite or buzzard — birds considered greedy scavengers. Shakespeare used it in \'Cymbeline\' to mean a knavish, greedy person.'),
  'PUTZ': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'From Yiddish \'pots\' — penis; meaning \'fool\' in US English.'),
  'RAPSCALLION': Etymology(meta: 'ARCHAIC · Victorian', note: '17th C alteration of \'rascal\'.'),
  'RASPBERRY': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'Cockney rhyming slang: \'raspberry tart\' = fart. Blowing a raspberry (the rude lip-buzzing noise) has been British playground currency since the 1890s.'),
  'RAT': Etymology(meta: '', note: 'From Old English \'raett\'. Rats have been associated with betrayal (they \'desert a sinking ship\') and disease since the Black Death (1347). \'You dirty rat!\' — often misattributed to James Cagney.'),
  'RATBAG': Etymology(meta: 'AU', note: 'Australian slang from the 1890s, literally a bag of rats — implying someone unpleasant or eccentric. Often used affectionately: \'you old ratbag\'.'),
  'RATS': Etymology(meta: '', note: 'Mild exclamation of frustration.'),
  'RECKON': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'Old English \'ge-recenian\' — to recount. Southern US retains \'I reckon\' where other dialects lost it.'),
  'RECREANT': Etymology(meta: 'ARCHAIC · archaic', note: 'From Old French \'recreant\' (surrendering, cowardly) — literally one who \'recries\' or yields. A medieval legal term: a knight who yielded in trial by combat was declared \'recreant\' and lost all rights.'),
  'ROASTER': Etymology(meta: 'SCO', note: 'Scottish slang for someone who makes a fool of themselves — they\'re \'getting roasted\'. Common in Glasgow and Edinburgh since the 1990s. \'Pure roaster\' is the intensified form.'),
  'ROGUE': Etymology(meta: 'archaic', note: 'Origin uncertain — possibly from Latin \'rogare\' (to beg). In 1572, the \'Vagabonds Act\' legally defined \'rogues\' as masterless men who could be whipped and branded. Now it\'s almost a compliment.'),
  'ROTTER': Etymology(meta: 'UK · historical', note: 'From \'rot\' — a person who is morally rotten. Peak usage was Edwardian (1900s-1910s), the era of Bertie Wooster. \'What a rotter!\' was about the strongest thing a gentleman would say.'),
  'RUDDY': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'A euphemism for \'bloody\', used since the 1910s. \'Ruddy\' means red-complexioned, so the semantic connection to \'bloody\' (blood-red) is transparent — but just indirect enough for broadcast.'),
  'SAD SACK': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'WWII cartoon by George Baker; \'a hapless loser\'.'),
  'SAKES': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'Regional US — \'sakes alive\', \'for Pete\'s sake\'.'),
  'SALTY': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: '2010s US internet slang; \'bitter or resentful\'. Earlier Navy slang too.'),
  'SAUSAGE': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: '\'Silly sausage\' is quintessential British affection-disguised-as-insult — used for children and adults who\'ve done something daft. \'Not a sausage\' (nothing) is Cockney rhyming slang from the 1930s.'),
  'SCALLYWAG': Etymology(meta: 'UK · historical', note: 'Origin uncertain — possibly from Scalloway in the Shetland Islands (known for small ponies, hence \'small/worthless\'). In post-Civil War US, \'scalawag\' was a white Southerner who cooperated with Reconstruction.'),
  'SCENERY CHEWER': Etymology(meta: '', note: 'Theatre criticism term for an actor so over-the-top they seem to be eating the set. Dorothy Parker reportedly described an actor as \'running the gamut of emotions from A to B\' — the chewer goes from A to Z.'),
  'SCHMUCK': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'From Yiddish \'shmok\' — penis; Yiddish origin keeps it strong in-community.'),
  'SCOUNDREL': Etymology(meta: 'Victorian', note: 'Origin disputed; 16th C.'),
  'SCUPPER': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'A scupper is a drain hole in a ship\'s deck. \'Scuppered\' means sunk or defeated — from deliberately opening the scuppers to flood a ship. \'Well, that\'s scuppered us\' means \'we\'re done for\'.'),
  'SCURVY': Etymology(meta: 'historical', note: 'The disease caused by vitamin C deficiency killed more sailors than combat. By the 16th century \'scurvy\' became an adjective meaning worthless or contemptible — \'thou scurvy knave\'. Shakespeare loved it.'),
  'SCUT': Etymology(meta: 'ARCHAIC · archaic', note: 'Originally the short erect tail of a hare or rabbit (from Middle English). Used as an insult meaning a contemptible person — literally calling someone a rabbit\'s backside.'),
  'SHIRKER': Etymology(meta: '', note: 'From German \'Schurke\' (scoundrel) or possibly from \'shark\' (a parasite). During WWI, \'shirker\' was a devastating accusation — white feathers were given to men suspected of avoiding service.'),
  'SHOOK': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: '2010s US hip-hop → internet slang; \'startled, shocked\'.'),
  'SHOOT': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'American euphemism for s-word; 19th C onwards.'),
  'SHUCKS': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'Originally \'husks of no value\' → worthless → mild exclamation.'),
  'SKIVER': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'Possibly from French \'esquiver\' (to dodge, slink away). Since the 1900s in British English, a skiver is someone who avoids work. \'Skiving off\' remains standard British slang for truancy.'),
  'SLACKER': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'From \'slack\' (loose, lazy). Used for draft dodgers in both World Wars. Richard Linklater\'s film \'Slacker\' (1990) reclaimed it for Generation X as an identity rather than an insult.'),
  'SMEG': Etymology(meta: 'FICTIONAL', note: 'Red Dwarf (1988) — invented profanity.'),
  'SNAFU': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'WWII US military acronym: Situation Normal, All F***ed Up.'),
  'SNAKE': Etymology(meta: '', note: 'Biblical origins — the serpent in Eden made snakes a symbol of treachery. \'Snake in the grass\' comes from Virgil\'s Eclogues (37 BC). Taylor Swift\'s fans reclaimed the snake emoji in 2017.'),
  'SNIT': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'American English from the 1930s — \'in a snit\' means in a state of agitation. Origin uncertain, possibly related to \'snot\' (both begin with an irritable \'sn-\' sound cluster).'),
  'SNOLLYGOSTER': Etymology(meta: 'ARCHAIC · Victorian', note: '19th C US — a shrewd, unprincipled politician.'),
  'SON OF A GUN': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'Naval origin — children born aboard ship near the guns.'),
  'SPIV': Etymology(meta: 'UK · historical', note: 'British slang from WWII for a black-market dealer — flashily dressed, dodgy goods. Origin uncertain, possibly Romani. The spiv was a stock character of British post-war culture, immortalised by Arthur Daley in \'Minder\'.'),
  'STINKER': Etymology(meta: '', note: 'From Old English \'stincan\' (to smell). \'Stinker\' has been an insult since the 17th century — originally quite strong, it migrated to playgrounds by the 1920s and is now wholly harmless.'),
  'STREWTH': Etymology(meta: 'AU', note: 'Contraction of \'God\'s truth!\' — attested from the 1890s. Became associated with Australian English through cricket commentary and 1970s TV. Richie Benaud reportedly used it on air.'),
  'STRUMPET': Etymology(meta: 'ARCHAIC · archaic', note: 'Origin uncertain — possibly from Latin \'stuprum\' (disgrace). Shakespeare used it over 20 times across his plays, most memorably Othello calling Desdemona one.'),
  'SUGAR': Etymology(meta: '', note: 'Stand-in for a stronger s-word; established 20th C.'),
  'SWAB': Etymology(meta: 'historical', note: 'A swab is a mop used to clean ship decks — the lowest job aboard. Calling someone a \'swab\' was standard pirate-era contempt for an inferior, dating to the 1690s.'),
  'TARFU': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'WWII US military acronym: Things Are Really F***ed Up.'),
  'TARNATION': Etymology(meta: 'US · Victorian', note: '18th C US; blend of \'eternal\' and \'damnation\'.'),
  'TATTLE': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'From Middle Dutch or Middle Low German \'tatelen\' (to babble). A \'tattletale\' tells on other children — perhaps the gravest social crime in playground politics, punishable by exclusion from games.'),
  'TEUCHTER': Etymology(meta: 'SCO', note: 'Glasgow slang for a rural Highlander, from Scots Gaelic. Used by Lowland Scots the way Londoners might say \'country bumpkin\'. Can be affectionate or cutting depending on tone.'),
  'TOAD': Etymology(meta: '', note: 'Toads have been associated with ugliness and poison since medieval times — witches supposedly used them in spells. As an insult since the 16th century, it means a repulsive or despicable person.'),
  'TOERAG': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'Originally the rag wrapped around a tramp\'s foot instead of a sock — hence the lowest of the low. Victorian in origin, it persists as a solid British insult meaning a despicable person.'),
  'TOSH': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: '19th C slang for rubbish; origin disputed.'),
  'TOSSER': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'From \'toss off\' — British slang for masturbation since the 1700s. A \'tosser\' is therefore literally a masturbator, but in practice it\'s a general insult for a contemptible idiot. Enduringly popular.'),
  'TRIPE': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'Tripe is stomach lining eaten as food — the word comes from Arabic \'therb\' (entrails). As slang for nonsense since the 1890s: \'what utter tripe!\' — equating someone\'s words with animal guts.'),
  'TRIPPIN': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: '1960s US drug slang → 1990s hip-hop; \'acting irrationally\'.'),
  'TURKEY': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: '1950s US; a flop or a fool.'),
  'TURNIP': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'Calling someone a turnip implies they have the intelligence of a root vegetable. \'Turnip\' as an insult dates to the 16th century. In football, England manager Graham Taylor was dubbed \'Turnip\' by tabloids after a 1992 defeat.'),
  'TWADDLE': Etymology(meta: '', note: 'Late 18th C, from \'twattle\' (prattle).'),
  'TWATS': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'Plural of \'twat\' — from Old Norse. Robert Browning famously misused it in \'Pippa Passes\' (1841), thinking it meant a nun\'s hat, after misreading a 17th-century poem.'),
  'TWERP': Etymology(meta: '', note: 'Origin uncertain — legend claims it derives from T.W. Earp, an Oxford undergraduate mocked by J.R.R. Tolkien in the 1910s. More likely just an expressive coinage. Means a silly, insignificant person.'),
  'TWIT': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'From \'twit\' (to taunt); as \'fool\' from 1920s RAF slang.'),
  'UFF DA': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'Minnesotan/Norwegian-American expression of dismay or effort.'),
  'UPSTAGE': Etymology(meta: '', note: 'Originally literal — old stages were raked (tilted), so \'upstage\' was further from the audience. An actor standing upstage forced others to turn away from the audience. Hence \'to upstage\' means to steal attention.'),
  'VARLET': Etymology(meta: 'ARCHAIC · Shakespearean', note: 'Medieval: a knight\'s attendant → rogue by 16th C.'),
  'VIPER': Etymology(meta: 'archaic', note: 'From Latin \'vipera\'. The Bible\'s \'brood of vipers\' (Matthew 3:7) established it as the strongest reptilian insult. Shakespeare used it in \'Richard II\'. Implies venomous treachery.'),
  'WACK': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: '1980s US hip-hop; \'bad, inferior\'.'),
  'WALLY': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: '1960s UK slang; disputed origin — possibly from \'Walter\'.'),
  'WANKER': Etymology(meta: 'UK', note: 'Strong insult in UK/AU; anatomical origin. Medium in AU, stronger in UK.'),
  'WASTREL': Etymology(meta: 'ARCHAIC · archaic', note: 'From \'waste\' + \'-rel\' (pejorative suffix, as in \'scoundrel\'). A wastrel squanders money, time, or talent. Victorian novelists loved it for dissolute younger sons frittering away family fortunes.'),
  'WEASEL': Etymology(meta: '', note: 'From Old English \'wesle\'. Weasels have been symbols of sneakiness since antiquity — Aristotle called them \'mischievous\'. \'Weasel words\' (evasive language) was coined by Theodore Roosevelt in 1916.'),
  'WEENIE': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'From \'wiener\' (Vienna sausage). As slang for penis since the 1900s, and as a mild insult for a timid or feeble person since the 1960s. SpongeBob\'s \'weenie hut\' cemented its playground status.'),
  'WICKED': Etymology(meta: 'US', note: 'New England intensifier (\'wicked good\'); regional since 19th C.'),
